    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "bfb0a0ebbf8ad7e8",
      "text": "FEASTfm Radio-Conferences\n\nLeading the way in combined local-and-global conversations.\n\nStructure\n\nFEASTfm radio conferences are a combination of the best of podcasting, a traditional phone-in radio show, and a conference - with the special ingredient of FEAST. \n\nThere is a three part structure (beginning, middle, and end) with radio programmes making the beginning and the end. The middle is some FEAST magic. \n\nIf you prefer to compare it with a conference then the beginning is like the opening keynote addresses - setting the scene and framing the discussions to come. The end is like the plenary - if you can imagine an excellent plenary. \n\nOur end “plenary” radio programme: \nRelates back to the first programme\nPulls in information generated afterwards through the FEAST magic\nHelps people to realise what an excellent experience it has all been\nSends them back out into their various situations energised and with new purpose.\n\nThe “FEAST magic middle”\n\nSo - what about the FEAST magic in between? \n\nFrom a radio perspective the middle part is like a radio phone-in. It allows people to respond to what they heard in the first programme. The FEAST magic is how they do that response, and how we feed it into the end programme.\n\nThe beginning radio programme is broadcast by a radio station, which also broadcasts the final programme. The programmes are also recorded as podcasts.\n\nListeners may listen to the first programme live, or via podcasts. If they listen to web-based broadcasts or podcasts they listen on their smart phones. When they give feedback, or ask questions, they don’t phone in live. They use WhatsApp. They don’t sent text messages on WhatsApp they send small sound files. \n\nThe FEAST magic is in with way the sound files are created and used. There are two kinds of FEAST magic. One relates to the way that we edit the small sound files to feed into the end radio programme. The other relates to the training courses we are planning to do for some FEAST participants to help them become mini sound studios. They won’t be sending in simple small sound files. They will be sending in mini podcasts. So, from some listeners we will be getting simple comments and questions, and from others we will be getting an edited local picture in sound. All this will be edited and fed into the radio programme that ends the conference.\n\nOver time, as FEAST increases its reach through a number of FEASTfm radio conferences, so the number of local mini-studios we have trained and equipped will increase, all adding to the magic.\n\nAs time passes the number of radio studios and radio stations that are linked through FEAST will increase. There will be a sharing of syndicated FEAST podcasts. A podcast which has been “the plenary” of a conference broadcast by one radio station may become source material for the “keynote” broadcast of a radio conference elsewhere. Any conference can feed into a related radio conference organised subsequently by another FEAST linked radio station.\n\nFEASTfm radio conferences provide a completely new integrated approach to globally scattered information-sharing and knowledge co-creation. You are invited to FEAST.\n\nThe first FEASTfm conference \n\nThe first FEASTfm conference will be broadcast by the radio station at SOAS - the School of Oriental and African Studies. \n\nThe topic is “conflict resolution”, with a focus on the problems faced by pastoralists in Africa as a result of climate change and other pressures on land use. Our panel includes guests from Ethiopia and Nigeria who are involved with the issues on the ground. \n\nOur sound medley at the start includes current recordings from people and places at different parts of the disputed grazing corridor in Nigeria.\n\nThe trigger for this topic was the recent resurgence of violence between pastoralists and farmers in Southern Kaduna, Nigeria.\n\nSOAS is part of London University and is celebrating its one hundredth anniversary. \n\nIt is the perfect host radio station to launch a totally new kind of radio conference. \n"
    },
